WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:06.380 --> 00:00:08.260
JOHN: Good morning,
and welcome to Talks

00:00:08.260 --> 00:00:10.520
at Google in Cambridge, Mass.

00:00:10.520 --> 00:00:14.105
Today, it is my great pleasure
to introduce Marc Abrahams.

00:00:15.960 --> 00:00:17.960
It's not every day
that we get to welcome

00:00:17.960 --> 00:00:21.120
the man "The Washington
Post" has called the nation's

00:00:21.120 --> 00:00:25.700
guru of academic grunge,
who's also a manga hero,

00:00:25.700 --> 00:00:27.630
but here we are.

00:00:27.630 --> 00:00:31.210
Mark's CV is far too
long to list here,

00:00:31.210 --> 00:00:34.250
but we know and love him
as Co-founder and Editor

00:00:34.250 --> 00:00:39.020
of "The Annals of Improbable
Research and the author

00:00:39.020 --> 00:00:41.280
of "This is Improbable"
and the book,

00:00:41.280 --> 00:00:42.910
which we're
expecting imminently,

00:00:42.910 --> 00:00:45.300
"This is Improbable Too."

00:00:45.300 --> 00:00:49.130
Not to mention Co-author of "The
Ig Nobel Cookbook, Volume One,"

00:00:49.130 --> 00:00:51.003
which frankly sounds terrifying.

00:00:52.720 --> 00:00:55.300
And of course, he's
the Founder and MC

00:00:55.300 --> 00:00:57.175
of the Ignoble Prize Ceremony.

00:00:58.600 --> 00:01:02.650
Little known fact, he's married
to psychologist Robin Abrahams,

00:01:02.650 --> 00:01:05.200
who writes the "Miss
Conduct" advice

00:01:05.200 --> 00:01:07.850
column in the Sunday
"Boston Globe" magazine.

00:01:09.260 --> 00:01:10.195
I love that column.

00:01:10.195 --> 00:01:11.510
Maybe you do, too.

00:01:11.510 --> 00:01:15.040
If any of you has
a friend who has

00:01:15.040 --> 00:01:18.850
a personal problem
or a social issue,

00:01:18.850 --> 00:01:21.280
I'm told that Robin
would welcome your input.

00:01:21.280 --> 00:01:26.670
All the questions that come
to the column are from readers

00:01:26.670 --> 00:01:28.380
and she's always
looking for those.

00:01:29.420 --> 00:01:31.570
So without further
ado, please join me

00:01:31.570 --> 00:01:33.757
in welcoming Marc Abrahams.

00:01:33.757 --> 00:01:34.691
[APPLAUSE]

00:01:34.691 --> 00:01:36.092
MARC ABRAHAMS: Thank you, John.

00:01:37.922 --> 00:01:38.880
Thanks very much, John.

00:01:40.590 --> 00:01:41.740
My name is Marc Abrahams.

00:01:41.740 --> 00:01:44.980
I am editor of this magazine.

00:01:44.980 --> 00:01:48.210
It's Called "The Annals
of Improbable Research."

00:01:48.210 --> 00:01:50.310
Some of you are very
familiar with it.

00:01:50.310 --> 00:01:52.430
Some of you probably
have never heard of it

00:01:52.430 --> 00:01:54.200
and are even on
the verge of being

00:01:54.200 --> 00:01:55.760
offended at what it might be.

00:01:57.550 --> 00:02:01.280
I'll distribute a couple copies
in our most traditional manner

00:02:01.280 --> 00:02:01.780
here.

00:02:05.160 --> 00:02:08.050
I've got a couple more later
on if anybody would like some.

00:02:09.600 --> 00:02:10.870
I collect things.

00:02:10.870 --> 00:02:12.850
I collect research.

00:02:12.850 --> 00:02:15.630
And I define that in the
broadest possible way.

00:02:15.630 --> 00:02:20.540
I collect research that makes
people laugh, and then think.

00:02:20.540 --> 00:02:24.780
These are real things
that are documented

00:02:24.780 --> 00:02:27.650
that when you first
encounter them are funny.

00:02:27.650 --> 00:02:30.230
There's something about
them that just is funny.

00:02:31.580 --> 00:02:33.170
But also, there's
something about them

00:02:33.170 --> 00:02:36.150
that a week later you find
it's still rattling around

00:02:36.150 --> 00:02:38.300
in your head, the
kind of thing that you

00:02:38.300 --> 00:02:41.150
want to tell your friends
about and argue about.

00:02:41.150 --> 00:02:43.710
So if it has both qualities,
it makes people laugh

00:02:43.710 --> 00:02:46.240
and then think, I want
to get a hold of it,

00:02:46.240 --> 00:02:47.210
put it in our magazine.

00:02:48.840 --> 00:02:50.870
I also write a
newspaper column in one

00:02:50.870 --> 00:02:53.230
of the British newspapers
with similar things.

00:02:53.230 --> 00:02:54.290
And I write other places.

00:02:54.290 --> 00:02:57.360
And then, every
year we give prizes.

00:02:57.360 --> 00:03:00.320
And that's mostly what I'm
going to show you about here.

00:03:19.200 --> 00:03:22.660
This research, I
hope you will agree,

00:03:22.660 --> 00:03:25.300
deserves to get
some kind of prize.

00:03:25.300 --> 00:03:27.100
[LAUGHTER]

00:03:27.100 --> 00:03:28.160
Let me show you another.

00:03:29.730 --> 00:03:35.610
This is a piece of a patent that
was granted in 1965 to George

00:03:35.610 --> 00:03:36.820
and Charlotte Blonsky.

00:03:36.820 --> 00:03:38.770
The Blonskys were
a married couple.

00:03:38.770 --> 00:03:41.420
They lived in New
York City at the time.

00:03:41.420 --> 00:03:44.880
They invented what they call
a device to assist women

00:03:44.880 --> 00:03:45.950
in giving birth.

00:03:47.320 --> 00:03:48.470
This is what it looks like.

00:03:49.540 --> 00:03:53.860
It's a large, round table with
some machinery underneath.

00:03:53.860 --> 00:03:56.570
When the woman is ready
to deliver her child,

00:03:56.570 --> 00:03:59.450
she lies on her
back on the table.

00:03:59.450 --> 00:04:01.690
They strap her down
to the table and then

00:04:01.690 --> 00:04:03.680
the table is rotated
at high speed

00:04:03.680 --> 00:04:06.570
and the child comes flying
out through centrifugal force.

00:04:07.760 --> 00:04:10.430
If you look closely at
this engineering diagram,

00:04:10.430 --> 00:04:18.519
you may decide that there is
at least one suboptimal thing

00:04:18.519 --> 00:04:19.730
in the design.

00:04:19.730 --> 00:04:22.400
I would point you especially
toward the part of it that's

00:04:22.400 --> 00:04:25.500
designed to catch the
child when it emerges.

00:04:25.500 --> 00:04:27.430
You may feel that
that's not quite

00:04:27.430 --> 00:04:30.342
adequate to the task,
what they've got there.

00:04:30.342 --> 00:04:32.680
And I'll show you
a third thing here.

00:04:32.680 --> 00:04:34.091
This is a biology paper.

00:04:34.091 --> 00:04:36.465
It was published in a biology
journal in the Netherlands.

00:04:38.160 --> 00:04:42.280
And it is the first
scientifically documented case

00:04:42.280 --> 00:04:46.986
of homosexual necrophilia
in the mallard duck.

00:04:49.662 --> 00:04:52.930
This won an Ig Nobel
Prize for this.

00:04:52.930 --> 00:04:57.012
This was completely
unknown to ornithologists

00:04:57.012 --> 00:04:57.720
when it happened.

00:05:01.530 --> 00:05:04.510
Each of those things I just
told you a little bit about

00:05:04.510 --> 00:05:06.585
has been awarded
an Ig Nobel Prize.

00:05:06.585 --> 00:05:08.960
And the prizes have that same
criterion that I described.

00:05:10.490 --> 00:05:12.880
If we've chosen well on
these things, each of them

00:05:12.880 --> 00:05:15.680
makes people laugh
and then think.

00:05:15.680 --> 00:05:18.560
We have been doing this
every year since 1991.

00:05:18.560 --> 00:05:22.840
We just had the 24th First
Annual Ig Nobel Prize Ceremony

00:05:22.840 --> 00:05:23.820
two weeks ago.

00:05:25.700 --> 00:05:27.820
You work with at
least one person

00:05:27.820 --> 00:05:32.160
who is vital to our-- let's
call it an enterprise.

00:05:33.310 --> 00:05:35.836
Quentin Smith, who I
think some of you know,

00:05:35.836 --> 00:05:40.080
has been our broadcast engineer
on the webcast for the past six

00:05:40.080 --> 00:05:41.230
or seven years.

00:05:41.230 --> 00:05:45.000
When he began, he was
an undergrad at MIT.

00:05:45.000 --> 00:05:48.330
And we've been webcasting
that ceremony since 1995.

00:05:48.330 --> 00:05:52.540
We were, I'm pretty sure, one
of the very first things ever

00:05:52.540 --> 00:05:54.260
to webcast anything.

00:05:54.260 --> 00:05:58.440
Robert T. Morris, who some
of you know that name,

00:05:58.440 --> 00:06:00.920
was our first
broadcast engineer.

00:06:00.920 --> 00:06:03.620
He was also I believe
the first person

00:06:03.620 --> 00:06:07.480
convicted on federal charges
of doing something that

00:06:07.480 --> 00:06:09.575
caused the entire
internet to collapse.

00:06:10.910 --> 00:06:12.650
It was not something
he was trying to do.

00:06:12.650 --> 00:06:13.660
He's a very nice guy.

00:06:15.130 --> 00:06:18.385
We have a nice history of good
and interesting engineers.

00:06:19.996 --> 00:06:22.570
I'll tell you a little
about the Ig Nobel Prizes.

00:06:24.860 --> 00:06:27.860
First of all, this
word "hiccups."

00:06:27.860 --> 00:06:29.170
You may see it repeated here.

00:06:29.170 --> 00:06:30.510
I hope you do.

00:06:30.510 --> 00:06:33.715
Otherwise, you have maybe some
kind of problem not related

00:06:33.715 --> 00:06:34.560
to hiccups.

00:06:34.560 --> 00:06:36.750
But hiccups, hiccups, hiccups.

00:06:37.770 --> 00:06:43.180
There is form of hiccups
that lasts a long time.

00:06:43.180 --> 00:06:45.560
Not just for a few
minutes or a few hours,

00:06:45.560 --> 00:06:48.020
but it goes on for
days, weeks, and months.

00:06:49.130 --> 00:06:51.300
It's rare, but it does happen.

00:06:51.300 --> 00:06:55.020
The medical profession calls
it intractable hiccups.

00:06:55.020 --> 00:06:58.110
They have names-- nice official
names for pretty much anything

00:06:58.110 --> 00:06:59.860
you can imagine
and lots of things

00:06:59.860 --> 00:07:01.430
you probably couldn't imagine.

00:07:02.640 --> 00:07:05.725
Doctors have never known how
to treat intractable hiccups.

00:07:07.400 --> 00:07:09.650
They've tried lots of things.

00:07:09.650 --> 00:07:12.770
Finally, a few years
ago, somebody-- a doctor

00:07:12.770 --> 00:07:15.840
in Tennessee came
up with what seems

00:07:15.840 --> 00:07:18.710
to be a reliable cure
for intractable hiccups.

00:07:20.940 --> 00:07:23.830
He tried it and he
published a medical report.

00:07:23.830 --> 00:07:24.450
Here it is.

00:07:24.450 --> 00:07:28.590
He calls it "Termination
of Intractable Hiccups

00:07:28.590 --> 00:07:34.060
with Digital Rectal Massage."

00:07:34.060 --> 00:07:38.850
Are there any questions about
any of the technical terms

00:07:38.850 --> 00:07:39.850
that I'm using here?

00:07:41.310 --> 00:07:43.770
Francis Fesmire is the
doctor who did this.

00:07:43.770 --> 00:07:48.210
We awarded him an Ig Nobel
Prize in Medicine for this.

00:07:48.210 --> 00:07:51.150
Here he is giving
his acceptance speech

00:07:51.150 --> 00:07:52.750
at the Ig Nobel Prize Ceremony.

00:07:55.960 --> 00:07:58.580
Since that time,
other doctors have

00:07:58.580 --> 00:08:00.630
seen his report,
other doctors who

00:08:00.630 --> 00:08:05.580
had similar patients that
they were trying to treat.

00:08:05.580 --> 00:08:07.980
And they have tried his
method and so far every case

00:08:07.980 --> 00:08:10.060
we've heard about-- a
small number of cases,

00:08:10.060 --> 00:08:14.060
but every one we've heard about,
the method has worked reliably.

00:08:14.060 --> 00:08:19.290
I have some unhappy, some
very sad news to report.

00:08:19.290 --> 00:08:22.480
Dr. Fesmire died a few
months ago unexpectedly.

00:08:23.910 --> 00:08:26.910
He worked at a large
medical center in Tennessee.

00:08:26.910 --> 00:08:29.050
And we've seen the
obituaries, and his colleagues

00:08:29.050 --> 00:08:30.230
are very sad.

00:08:30.230 --> 00:08:34.471
He was, obviously, a
beloved, in many ways, man.

00:08:34.471 --> 00:08:35.929
I'd gotten to know
him fairly well.

00:08:35.929 --> 00:08:38.799
He liked to come back every few
years to the Ig Nobel Ceremony

00:08:38.799 --> 00:08:41.159
and do what you see here.

00:08:41.159 --> 00:08:43.700
And he told me that
one of his dreams

00:08:43.700 --> 00:08:46.610
was that someday he would be
able to travel around with me,

00:08:46.610 --> 00:08:49.130
especially when I go
to Europe and do events

00:08:49.130 --> 00:08:51.680
with some of the Ig
Nobel Prize Winners,

00:08:51.680 --> 00:08:53.140
that he would come
along and he'd

00:08:53.140 --> 00:08:56.840
be able to explain his
technique to people

00:08:56.840 --> 00:08:59.015
around the world as part
of an Ig Nobel event.

00:09:00.920 --> 00:09:03.570
But he died and that's
never going to happen.

00:09:04.840 --> 00:09:07.140
So I would like to
ask a little favor,

00:09:07.140 --> 00:09:10.800
even though you don't know
me and I don't know you.

00:09:10.800 --> 00:09:14.960
Would you please join me just
for a moment in a small tribute

00:09:14.960 --> 00:09:16.180
to Dr. Fesmire?

00:09:16.180 --> 00:09:19.900
Could you raise a finger
in honor of Dr. Fesmire?

00:09:19.900 --> 00:09:20.890
Thank you.

00:09:20.890 --> 00:09:21.390
Thank you.

00:09:22.330 --> 00:09:22.830
All right.

00:09:24.350 --> 00:09:27.100
So this again is the
criterion for things.

00:09:27.100 --> 00:09:28.280
And it's just this.

00:09:28.280 --> 00:09:32.460
It's got to be real and it's
got to make people laugh.

00:09:32.460 --> 00:09:33.150
People anywhere.

00:09:33.150 --> 00:09:35.070
People who aren't
familiar with it at all.

00:09:36.065 --> 00:09:37.690
If it's going to win
an Ig Nobel Prize,

00:09:37.690 --> 00:09:39.860
make people laugh
and then think.

00:09:39.860 --> 00:09:44.690
We get something like 9,000
new nominations every year.

00:09:44.690 --> 00:09:47.130
And we-- and we is
a lot of us, mostly

00:09:47.130 --> 00:09:49.810
volunteers-- are always
looking for things, too.

00:09:49.810 --> 00:09:51.330
But we get floods of things.

00:09:51.330 --> 00:09:53.310
Little floods
coming in every day.

00:09:54.810 --> 00:09:57.440
And we give just
10 prizes a year.

00:09:57.440 --> 00:10:01.180
And they're not necessarily
restricted to recent things.

00:10:01.180 --> 00:10:05.080
We can, by our own
rules, go back up

00:10:05.080 --> 00:10:06.390
to about 50 years or so.

00:10:06.390 --> 00:10:10.140
As long as there's somebody
still alive who knew the person

00:10:10.140 --> 00:10:12.790
and could come and
talk about that, then

00:10:12.790 --> 00:10:14.740
it's OK to give that a prize.

00:10:14.740 --> 00:10:17.710
The oldest we've ever given,
or the farthest back we went

00:10:17.710 --> 00:10:18.810
was about 15 years ago.

00:10:18.810 --> 00:10:21.050
We gave a prize to
the three people

00:10:21.050 --> 00:10:23.875
who were responsible
for naming Murphy's law.

00:10:24.880 --> 00:10:27.660
You know Murphy's law, that
great engineering principle

00:10:27.660 --> 00:10:29.990
that if something can
go wrong, it will.

00:10:29.990 --> 00:10:33.750
And that was born in an
engineering project that

00:10:33.750 --> 00:10:36.210
happened at Edwards
Air Force Base, which

00:10:36.210 --> 00:10:40.220
had a slightly different
name back in the late 1940s.

00:10:40.220 --> 00:10:41.750
An incident that happened there.

00:10:41.750 --> 00:10:44.990
And it involved Captain
Murphy of the US Army Air

00:10:44.990 --> 00:10:49.060
Corps, whose name ended
up in Murphy's law,

00:10:49.060 --> 00:10:50.610
and several other people.

00:10:50.610 --> 00:10:53.850
Murphy's son came
to our ceremony.

00:10:53.850 --> 00:10:56.620
One of the co-winners
was the leader

00:10:56.620 --> 00:11:01.560
of the project which led to the
birth of the name Murphy's law.

00:11:01.560 --> 00:11:04.040
And it's somebody
who hated Murphy.

00:11:04.040 --> 00:11:07.050
And it's somebody who devoted
the rest of his life trying

00:11:07.050 --> 00:11:09.850
to convince the world
that Murphy gets

00:11:09.850 --> 00:11:12.010
too much credit
for Murphy's law.

00:11:15.350 --> 00:11:19.930
If you win an Ig Nobel
Prize-- first of all,

00:11:19.930 --> 00:11:23.550
before I explain
this, in most cases

00:11:23.550 --> 00:11:28.460
we will get in touch
quietly and offer the prize.

00:11:28.460 --> 00:11:32.580
And if somebody declines the
honor, if somebody says no,

00:11:32.580 --> 00:11:33.540
that's fine.

00:11:33.540 --> 00:11:35.890
And that's the end of it
and we never tell anybody.

00:11:37.240 --> 00:11:41.260
Happily for us, almost everybody
who's offered an Ig Nobel Prize

00:11:41.260 --> 00:11:42.810
decides to accept.

00:11:42.810 --> 00:11:43.825
And here's what they.

00:11:43.825 --> 00:11:45.362
They get an Ig Nobel Prize.

00:11:45.362 --> 00:11:46.820
That's what you're
looking at here.

00:11:46.820 --> 00:11:48.920
It's a different
design every year.

00:11:48.920 --> 00:11:51.000
They're always made of
extremely cheap materials.

00:11:52.320 --> 00:11:54.680
This is from last year, 2013.

00:11:54.680 --> 00:11:58.780
And the design that year was
a frame with a glass front.

00:11:58.780 --> 00:12:03.190
And under the glass, there
was a hammer and an indication

00:12:03.190 --> 00:12:06.130
there-- a statement,
"In case of emergency,

00:12:06.130 --> 00:12:08.790
use hammer to break glass."

00:12:08.790 --> 00:12:10.300
So you get that.

00:12:10.300 --> 00:12:12.080
You also get a
piece of paper that

00:12:12.080 --> 00:12:14.240
says you've won
an Ig Nobel Prize.

00:12:14.240 --> 00:12:16.750
And the piece of paper is
signed by several people

00:12:16.750 --> 00:12:18.560
who have Nobel Prizes.

00:12:18.560 --> 00:12:20.530
So it's a nice piece of paper.

00:12:21.600 --> 00:12:26.220
And there is a tradition that
a lot of the winners follow.

00:12:27.270 --> 00:12:29.730
And they seem to keep inventing
it independently, too.

00:12:29.730 --> 00:12:33.340
They'll take this piece
of paper home with them

00:12:33.340 --> 00:12:36.710
to whatever country they'd come
from to come to the ceremony

00:12:36.710 --> 00:12:39.390
and put it in a
nice frame and then

00:12:39.390 --> 00:12:41.310
hang it in their home
right above the toilet.

00:12:46.950 --> 00:12:51.340
We don't have any money, so
we can't offer cash, alas,

00:12:51.340 --> 00:12:52.580
to the winners.

00:12:52.580 --> 00:12:55.210
Just because we don't
have cash to offer.

00:12:55.210 --> 00:12:58.111
But we did finally figure
out a way, even on that,

00:12:58.111 --> 00:12:59.735
that we could overcome
that limitation.

00:13:01.480 --> 00:13:07.075
This past year each of the
winners received $10 trillion.

00:13:08.870 --> 00:13:10.920
Each of the winners,
each of the winning teams

00:13:10.920 --> 00:13:13.765
received a $10 trillion
bill from Zimbabwe.

00:13:15.080 --> 00:13:17.820
You may remember Zimbabwe
had a little incident lasted

00:13:17.820 --> 00:13:19.445
about a year and a
half with inflation.

00:13:19.445 --> 00:13:21.180
And they were--
by the end of it,

00:13:21.180 --> 00:13:25.210
they were printing bills with
a face value of $100 million.

00:13:25.210 --> 00:13:28.880
The government
official in Zimbabwe

00:13:28.880 --> 00:13:31.855
responsible for doing that
was awarded an Ig Nobel Prize.

00:13:32.920 --> 00:13:35.360
He, at the same time,
was having a government

00:13:35.360 --> 00:13:40.880
print some bills that had a
face value of $100 trillion

00:13:40.880 --> 00:13:46.520
and other bills that
had a face value $0.01.

00:13:46.520 --> 00:13:48.910
And he published
a book to explain

00:13:48.910 --> 00:13:51.540
to the public in Zimbabwe
and the rest of the world

00:13:51.540 --> 00:13:52.590
why he was doing this.

00:13:52.590 --> 00:13:56.550
And he said that when you're
spending these large amounts

00:13:56.550 --> 00:13:59.400
of money, you still
have to make change.

00:14:00.714 --> 00:14:06.980
[LAUGHTER]

