00:24:58.712 --> 00:25:00.545
We give a prize in the
field of Archaeology.

00:25:01.560 --> 00:25:05.650
Went to a team from
Canada and the US.

00:25:05.650 --> 00:25:09.925
They were awarded their prize
for parboiling a dead shrew.

00:25:11.510 --> 00:25:13.830
A shrew, you probably
know, is a small animal

00:25:13.830 --> 00:25:15.350
about the size of a mouse.

00:25:15.350 --> 00:25:18.040
And it looks fairly
like a mouse.

00:25:18.040 --> 00:25:20.360
They parboiled a
dead shrew and then

00:25:20.360 --> 00:25:24.280
swallowed that shrew
without chewing it.

00:25:24.280 --> 00:25:26.580
They were careful
not to chew it.

00:25:26.580 --> 00:25:29.230
And then they carefully
examined everything

00:25:29.230 --> 00:25:32.450
excreted by the test
subject who ate that

00:25:32.450 --> 00:25:35.590
during the next several days.

00:25:35.590 --> 00:25:40.000
They did this so they could
see which bones would dissolve

00:25:40.000 --> 00:25:42.910
inside the human
digestive system

00:25:42.910 --> 00:25:44.380
and which bones would not.

00:25:46.280 --> 00:25:48.080
They published a paper on it.

00:25:48.080 --> 00:25:50.210
The paper's called
"Human Digestive Effects

00:25:50.210 --> 00:25:52.680
on a Micromammalian Skeleton."

00:25:52.680 --> 00:25:56.668
It's got details and
photographs of the work.

00:25:58.460 --> 00:25:59.750
And they got a big surprise.

00:25:59.750 --> 00:26:04.900
They had expected that the
smallest bones, many of them

00:26:04.900 --> 00:26:06.340
would be dissolved.

00:26:06.340 --> 00:26:09.150
Some of the medium-sized
bones might suffer some damage

00:26:09.150 --> 00:26:12.030
from the digestive juices.

00:26:12.030 --> 00:26:14.780
And that the big bones
would be largely intact.

00:26:14.780 --> 00:26:16.490
That's not what happened.

00:26:16.490 --> 00:26:19.460
What happened was
even the biggest bones

00:26:19.460 --> 00:26:21.290
were substantially dissolved.

00:26:21.290 --> 00:26:23.830
And they were kind of
shocked to see this.

00:26:23.830 --> 00:26:26.175
This was completely against
anybody's expectation.

00:26:27.217 --> 00:26:29.050
They don't discuss it
too much in the paper,

00:26:29.050 --> 00:26:31.970
but this also could be
a very shocking thing

00:26:31.970 --> 00:26:33.660
to an awful lot
of people who are

00:26:33.660 --> 00:26:37.285
archaeologists because there
are an awful lot of papers that

00:26:37.285 --> 00:26:41.570
have been published for decades
interpreting collections

00:26:41.570 --> 00:26:42.580
of bones.

00:26:42.580 --> 00:26:45.740
Typically, of some small
animal and some large animal

00:26:45.740 --> 00:26:47.820
in the same place,
where it seems evident

00:26:47.820 --> 00:26:51.340
that the large animal
ate the small animal.

00:26:51.340 --> 00:26:54.810
And an awful lot
of the explanation

00:26:54.810 --> 00:26:57.470
that the archaeologists
came up with

00:26:57.470 --> 00:27:01.280
had to do with because there
are only these bones left

00:27:01.280 --> 00:27:03.840
and these ones are damaged,
the large animal must

00:27:03.840 --> 00:27:07.770
have had massive jaws and
a certain kind of teeth.

00:27:07.770 --> 00:27:11.140
This paper says that
is not necessarily so.

00:27:11.140 --> 00:27:13.227
So it might be
kind of interesting

00:27:13.227 --> 00:27:14.810
over the next few
years to see if this

00:27:14.810 --> 00:27:16.559
gets noticed in the
archaeology community.

