00:40:36.106 --> 00:40:39.339
AUDIENCE: What caused you
to decide to do all this?

00:40:39.339 --> 00:40:41.630
MARC ABRAHAMS: What caused
me to decide to do all this?

00:40:43.660 --> 00:40:45.140
I was a peculiar little kid.

00:40:45.140 --> 00:40:50.437
And most of the pieces
of what I'm doing now I

00:40:50.437 --> 00:40:51.520
was doing as a little kid.

00:40:51.520 --> 00:40:53.850
I liked to read lots
of science stuff.

00:40:53.850 --> 00:40:57.420
And I liked to write what I
thought were funny things.

00:40:57.420 --> 00:41:00.590
And I also very early on
started reading newspapers.

00:41:00.590 --> 00:41:03.430
And I especially liked
the odd, little stories

00:41:03.430 --> 00:41:06.415
that I would see tucked away
in the corners of pages.

00:41:06.415 --> 00:41:09.720
Because newspapers
have always had a--

00:41:09.720 --> 00:41:12.430
Before the internet, where
space stopped mattering so much,

00:41:12.430 --> 00:41:14.960
they always had the problem
that you have to fill the page.

00:41:14.960 --> 00:41:17.841
And if you got a corner, you
fill it with something short.

00:41:17.841 --> 00:41:19.340
And if you had a
taste for that, you

00:41:19.340 --> 00:41:21.860
could notice that
newspapers all the time

00:41:21.860 --> 00:41:23.940
would have these odd,
little stories that

00:41:23.940 --> 00:41:26.556
were very short and
memorable to me.

00:41:26.556 --> 00:41:28.430
So I used to cut those
out and collect those.

00:41:28.430 --> 00:41:29.990
And I'm still sort
of doing that.

00:41:31.160 --> 00:41:33.770
And then I went off
and studied math

00:41:33.770 --> 00:41:35.579
and got involved
with computer stuff

00:41:35.579 --> 00:41:37.870
and was doing that because
I didn't think as a grown up

00:41:37.870 --> 00:41:41.790
you could get paid or make a
living doing this other stuff.

00:41:41.790 --> 00:41:44.602
But I kept doing it
and just giving it

00:41:44.602 --> 00:41:45.560
to a couple of friends.

00:41:45.560 --> 00:41:47.590
You know, writing things,
collecting things.

00:41:47.590 --> 00:41:50.650
And then one day,
I-- by this time,

00:41:50.650 --> 00:41:53.380
I had started a little
software company of my own.

00:41:53.380 --> 00:41:55.450
But one day I just
started wondering,

00:41:55.450 --> 00:41:57.820
could I get some of my
stuff published someplace?

00:41:57.820 --> 00:42:01.690
If I send it in to some journal,
can I get something published?

00:42:01.690 --> 00:42:04.870
So I sent some of my
stuff off to a journal

00:42:04.870 --> 00:42:06.080
with a little cover letter.

00:42:06.080 --> 00:42:08.410
And a few weeks later I got
a phone call from somebody

00:42:08.410 --> 00:42:11.530
saying, hi, I'm the
publisher of the journal.

00:42:12.570 --> 00:42:13.930
Got your articles.

00:42:13.930 --> 00:42:15.760
Would you be the
editor of the journal?

00:42:17.188 --> 00:42:21.880
[LAUGHTER]

00:42:21.880 --> 00:42:23.310
So I went and talked to him.

00:42:23.310 --> 00:42:24.890
And I couldn't resist this.

00:42:24.890 --> 00:42:27.680
This was the chance
to do all this.

00:42:27.680 --> 00:42:30.030
And there was a long
history leading up to then.

00:42:30.030 --> 00:42:32.480
That journal had been started
by a couple of scientists

00:42:32.480 --> 00:42:35.150
in the 1950s, and it had
gone through tremendous highs

00:42:35.150 --> 00:42:36.840
and lows and been
kind of wrecked,

00:42:36.840 --> 00:42:39.770
then bought by a big
British science publisher

00:42:39.770 --> 00:42:40.940
just at this time.

00:42:40.940 --> 00:42:43.146
So it was a kind of
happy conjunction.

00:42:43.146 --> 00:42:44.520
So I started doing
that at night.

00:42:44.520 --> 00:42:46.895
For the next four years, I
was running my little software

00:42:46.895 --> 00:42:48.310
company, doing this at night.

00:42:48.310 --> 00:42:50.920
I started the Ig Nobel
Ceremony and all kinds

00:42:50.920 --> 00:42:55.410
of mostly good things and many
wonderful things happened.

00:42:55.410 --> 00:42:56.950
I've been very happy.

00:42:56.950 --> 00:42:58.970
It's been growing and
infecting the world.

00:42:58.970 --> 00:43:02.450
And now we have a
big gang of people

00:43:02.450 --> 00:43:05.000
all around the world
who seem to devote,

00:43:05.000 --> 00:43:06.840
I think in some
cases, maybe too much

00:43:06.840 --> 00:43:09.120
of their lives to
being part of this.

00:43:09.120 --> 00:43:12.470
But I'm very happy at
the way it's working out.

00:43:12.470 --> 00:43:15.590
And I invite all of
you to be part of this.

00:43:15.590 --> 00:43:17.350
If you run across
something that you

00:43:17.350 --> 00:43:20.070
think people should
know about, just

00:43:20.070 --> 00:43:22.160
something that makes
you laugh and makes you

00:43:22.160 --> 00:43:26.260
think, then the
favor I ask of you,

00:43:26.260 --> 00:43:28.640
in addition to-- thank you
for the favor you granted

00:43:28.640 --> 00:43:33.070
of celebrating Dr. Fesmire,
is the next time you

00:43:33.070 --> 00:43:36.500
run across something that
really hits you that way,

00:43:36.500 --> 00:43:38.681
after you tell your three
best friends about it,

00:43:38.681 --> 00:43:40.430
if you want the rest
of the world to know,

00:43:40.430 --> 00:43:41.860
just drop me a line.

00:43:41.860 --> 00:43:45.357
And I always give people
credit for discovering it,

00:43:45.357 --> 00:43:46.440
unless they don't want it.

00:43:46.440 --> 00:43:50.760
If you want your name to not
appear, that's absolutely fine.

00:43:50.760 --> 00:43:51.740
Just say something.

00:43:53.472 --> 00:43:54.305
Any other questions?

00:43:57.040 --> 00:43:59.870
AUDIENCE: So I find what you're
doing to be pretty hilarious.

00:43:59.870 --> 00:44:03.400
That said, there's
kind of view or culture

00:44:03.400 --> 00:44:05.150
right now where it's
sort of anti-science.

00:44:05.150 --> 00:44:09.660
And a lot of views that research
funding is a waste in science.

00:44:09.660 --> 00:44:11.420
Do you have any
thoughts about if this

00:44:11.420 --> 00:44:12.447
impacts that either way?

00:44:12.447 --> 00:44:13.405
MARC ABRAHAMS: Oh, yes.

00:44:15.290 --> 00:44:19.070
When we started doing this
stuff, a lot of people

00:44:19.070 --> 00:44:22.760
assumed, and they
still-- people new to it

00:44:22.760 --> 00:44:25.350
will assume from the
name or something else

00:44:25.350 --> 00:44:31.496
that we must be out to trash
scientists, and technology,

00:44:31.496 --> 00:44:32.870
and medicine, and
all that stuff.

00:44:34.070 --> 00:44:37.890
And no, not at all.

00:44:37.890 --> 00:44:41.440
What we're about, at least
what I think we're about,

00:44:41.440 --> 00:44:46.430
is trying to tempt people
into being a little more

00:44:46.430 --> 00:44:48.360
curious about things.

00:44:48.360 --> 00:44:52.180
And also, maybe to
my grand ambition,

00:44:52.180 --> 00:44:57.320
to get people a little more
in the habit of when you hear

00:44:57.320 --> 00:45:00.280
something, when somebody
important tells you something--

00:45:00.280 --> 00:45:01.310
this is great.

00:45:01.310 --> 00:45:03.430
This is wonderful,
this discovery.

00:45:03.430 --> 00:45:10.050
Or, that medicine is bad or that
video games are bad, whatever.

00:45:10.050 --> 00:45:11.520
Or this person is terrible.

00:45:11.520 --> 00:45:15.030
That when some important
person tells you something,

00:45:15.030 --> 00:45:17.280
you can accept that if you want.

00:45:17.280 --> 00:45:20.280
But you can also look at it
and make your own decision.

00:45:21.810 --> 00:45:24.020
So the general thing
that I really love--

00:45:24.020 --> 00:45:27.390
and I hope this is
what is at work here--

00:45:27.390 --> 00:45:31.410
is things that are right on
the edge, where at first glance

00:45:31.410 --> 00:45:35.020
it's not possible for
anybody at first glance

00:45:35.020 --> 00:45:38.480
to know whether this is a good
or a bad thing, or valuable,

00:45:38.480 --> 00:45:39.080
or worthless.

00:45:39.080 --> 00:45:40.250
It's just not possible.

00:45:40.250 --> 00:45:42.770
You have to look into
it in more detail.

00:45:42.770 --> 00:45:44.765
And then it may not
be possible even then.

00:45:44.765 --> 00:45:46.450
It may play out over years.

00:45:48.000 --> 00:45:51.490
so trying to promote
things in both ends.

00:45:51.490 --> 00:45:53.110
For bad stuff--
yeah, I would love

00:45:53.110 --> 00:45:56.560
people to look harder at the
bad stuff and realize it's bad.

00:45:57.720 --> 00:45:59.360
But on the other
end, I really want

00:45:59.360 --> 00:46:01.077
people to look at
everything else

00:46:01.077 --> 00:46:02.660
and think that what
you're looking at,

00:46:02.660 --> 00:46:03.743
you may be laughing at it.

00:46:03.743 --> 00:46:06.500
But that may turn out to
be something you decide

00:46:06.500 --> 00:46:09.160
is one of the best parts of
your life a few years from now.

00:46:09.160 --> 00:46:11.275
So don't be hasty in
making those judgments.

00:46:12.810 --> 00:46:16.916
It's a tough kind of-- and maybe
a crazy thing to want to do,

00:46:16.916 --> 00:46:19.290
but that's what I want to do
and that's what we're doing.

00:46:20.420 --> 00:46:22.720
So did that answer the question?

00:46:22.720 --> 00:46:23.520
Thanks.

00:46:23.520 --> 00:46:26.069
OK, well, I won't keep you
from lunch and whatever.

00:46:26.069 --> 00:46:28.110
Again, thank you very,
very much for inviting me.

00:46:28.110 --> 00:46:31.230
I feel very honored and very
proud and happy to be here.

00:46:31.230 --> 00:46:31.910
Thank you.

00:46:31.910 --> 00:46:33.460
[APPLAUSE]

